{"title_page": "Polish Fantasy (Paderewski)", "text_new": "The '''Polish Fantasy in G sharp minor''', Op.19 (French: '''''Fantaisie polonaise sur des th\u00e8mes originaux'''''), is a work for piano and orchestra composed in 1893 by [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]]. It was first performed at the [[Norwich Festival]] in [[England]] the same year, where it achieved success and became a frequent addition to Paderewswki's concert repertoire.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://polishmusic.usc.edu/research/publications/polish-music-journal/vol4no2/programmes-notes/|title=Analytical Notes on Paderewski\u2019s Programmes (1895-1908)|last=Krehbiel|first=Henry|website=Polish Music Center|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> It is characterized by expressive themes, drawing influences from Polish folk music, and was often played by Paderewski at his concerts to remind audiences of the existence of [[History_of_Poland_(1795\u20131918)|then-occupied Poland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://culture.pl/en/work/polish-fantasy-in-g-sharp-minor-op-19-ignacy-jan-paderewski |title=Polish Fantasy in G Sharp Minor, Op. 19 - Ignacy Jan Paderewski |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe work was dedicated to Princess Rachel de Brancovan.\n\n==Instrumentation==\nThe piece is scored for solo piano, 3 [[flutes]], 3 [[oboes]], 2 [[clarinets]], 2 [[bassoons]], 4 [[French horn|horns]], 2 [[trumpets]], 3 [[trombones]], [[tuba]], [[timpani]], [[percussion]], [[harp]], and [[string instrument|strings]]. A typical performance lasts around 21 minutes.\n\n==Structure==\nAlthough it is one piece, the Fantasy can be divided into four parts:\n\n# ''Allegro moderato'' ([[G sharp minor]])\n# ''Vivace non troppo, ma poi molto accelerando'' ([[C major]])\n# ''Andante molto sostenuto'' ([[G sharp minor]])\n# ''Allegro giocoso'' ([[A flat major]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Polish_Fantasy,_Op.19_(Paderewski,_Ignacy_Jan)|cname=Polish Fantasy, Op.19}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Ignacy Jan Paderewski]]\n\n[[Category:1893 compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions in G-sharp minor]]\n[[Category:Fantasias (music)]]\n[[Category:Compositions for piano and orchestra]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Polish Fantasy in G sharp minor''', Op.19 (French: '''''Fantaisie polonaise sur des th\u00e8mes originaux'''''), is a work for piano and orchestra composed in 1893 by [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]]. It was first performed at the [[Norwich Festival]] in [[England]] the same year, where it achieved success and became a frequent addition to Paderewswki's concert repertoire.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://polishmusic.usc.edu/research/publications/polish-music-journal/vol4no2/programmes-notes/|title=Analytical Notes on Paderewski\u2019s Programmes (1895-1908)|last=Krehbiel|first=Henry|website=Polish Music Center|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> It is characterized by expressive themes, drawing influences from Polish folk music, and was often played by Paderewski at his concerts to remind audiences of the existence of [[History_of_Poland_(1795\u20131918)|then-occupied Poland]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://culture.pl/en/work/polish-fantasy-in-g-sharp-minor-op-19-ignacy-jan-paderewski |title=Polish Fantasy in G Sharp Minor, Op. 19 - Ignacy Jan Paderewski |access-date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe work was dedicated to Princess Rachel de Brancovan.\n\n==Instrumentation==\nThe piece is scored for solo piano, 3 [[flutes]], 3 [[oboes]], 2 [[clarinets]], 2 [[bassoons]], 4 [[French horn|horns]], 2 [[trumpets]], 3 [[trombones]], [[tuba]], [[timpani]], [[percussion]], [[harp]], and [[strings]]. A typical performance lasts around 21 minutes.\n\n==Structure==\nAlthough it is one piece, the Fantasy can be divided into four parts:\n\n# ''Allegro moderato'' ([[G sharp minor]])\n# ''Vivace non troppo, ma poi molto accelerando'' ([[C major]])\n# ''Andante molto sostenuto'' ([[G sharp minor]])\n# ''Allegro giocoso'' ([[A flat major]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Polish_Fantasy,_Op.19_(Paderewski,_Ignacy_Jan)|cname=Polish Fantasy, Op.19}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Ignacy Jan Paderewski]]\n\n[[Category:1893 compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions in G-sharp minor]]\n[[Category:Fantasias (music)]]\n[[Category:Compositions for piano and orchestra]]\n", "name_user": "TheAwesomeHwyh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:strings\u2192string instrument", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polish_Fantasy_(Paderewski)"}
{"title_page": "Carlos T. Mock", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Carlos T. Mock\n| image            = CarlosTMock.jpg\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1956|01|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| language         = [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[French language|French]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[University of Puerto Rico School of Medicine]]\n| occupation       = [[Physician]] [[Ob/Gyn]], [[activist]], [[novelist]], [[poet]]\n| nationality      = American ([[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]])\n| partner          = Bill Rattan\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.carlostmock.com/|www.CarlosTMock.com}}\n}}\n\nDr. '''Carlos T. Mock''' (born January 16, 1956) is a Puerto Rican physician, gay activist, journalist, and writer who has published both works in the medical profession, works of fiction, non-fiction, and poetry.\n\n==Life==\nMock was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].  He left Puerto Rico upon graduating from high school and attended [[The Johns Hopkins University]] in Baltimore, Maryland where he graduated [[Cum Laude]] in 1976 with a BA with a double major in Chemistry and Spanish Literature.  He then attended The [[University of Puerto Rico School of Medicine]] in San Juan where he obtained a [[Physician|MD]] in 1980.\n\nHe then did a flexible [[Internship (medicine)|internship]] at the [[United States Public Health Service|USPH]] Service Hospital in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] and then did a four-year residency in [[Obstetrics and gynaecology|Obstetrics and Gynecology]] at [[Stroger Hospital|Cook County Hospital]] in [[Chicago, Illinois]], graduating in 1985.\n\nMock then joined a private place group at the Glen Ellyn Clinic where he practiced Obstetrics and Gynecology until 1996.  He developed an interest in [[infertility]] and [[twin]] pregnancies which led to the publication of a medical paper in the later topic.\n\nHe is a Life Fellow of the [[American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists]] and a Life Member of the [[American Medical Association]].\n\nDue to complications from [[HIV]] therapy, he became disabled in May 1996.  He currently lives in Chicago, Illinois and [[Three Oaks, Michigan]] with his partner, Bill Rattan.\n\n==Activism==\nWhile at practice in the Glen Ellyn Clinic, Mock experienced first-hand the discrimination in the workforce against [[GLBT]] physicians when one of his colleagues was fired for being gay.  This, along with his HIV diagnosis, which forced him to retire, caused him to join the Board of [[Equality Illinois]] where he founded the Capitol Club.,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.chicagogayhistory.com/biography.html?id=771|title = Chicago Gay History|date = 2007-05-23|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> the fundraising arm of the organization, where he served from 2000 until 2009.  His fundraising efforts were instrumental in the passage of the Human Rights Act of Illinois in 2005,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www3.illinois.gov/pressreleases/ShowPressRelease.cfm?SubjectID=3&RecNum=3636 |title=Illinois Government News Network |date=January 21, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143112/http://www3.illinois.gov/pressreleases/ShowPressRelease.cfm?SubjectID=3&RecNum=3636 |archivedate=2015-04-27 }}</ref> prohibiting discrimination based upon sexual orientation and gender identity in Illinois. For his work he was inducted into the [[Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame]] in 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chicagolgbthalloffame.org/mock-carlos/|title=Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n\n==Literary career==\nMock started writing in 2001.  He was first published in 2003 when Floricanto Press published Borrowing Time, A Latino Sexual Odyssey, which was later released in paperback in 2006.  This was followed by five other publications.  Since then he has contributed to The [[Chicago Tribune]], [[Windy City Times]], Ambiente Magazine (in Miami, Florida) and the web magazines: The Billerico Project and OpEd News.\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Articles===\n* Twin Reversed Arterial Perfusion Syndrome, acephalic presentating at full term, Robert Roger Lebel, MD, Carlos Mock, MD, Jeannette Israel, MD, William Senica, MD, Fetus Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sonoworld.com/fetus/page.aspx?id=309|title = Twin reversed arterial perfusion syndrome, acephalic presenting at full term|date = 2 June 1994|accessdate = |website = Fetus Magazine|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Mock Views:  The Death of a Great Pope<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Mock-Views-The-Death-of-a-Great-Pope/7948.html|title = Mock Views: The Death of a Great Pope|date = 2005-04-13|accessdate = |website = Windy City Times|publisher = Windy City Media Group|last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The New Faces of Puerto Rican Lesbian Activism<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/The-New-Faces-of-Puerto-Rican-Lesbian-Activism/9342.html|title = The New Faces of Puerto Rican Lesbian Activism|date = 2005-09-01|accessdate = |website = Windy City Times|publisher = Windy City Media Group|last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Puerto Ricans must address America's race and class divide<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.opednews.com/articles/opedne_carlos_t_060826_puerto_ricans_must_a.htm|title = Puerto Ricans must address America's race and class divide|date = 2006-08-27|accessdate = |website = OpEd News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* With these words, let us wed<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2008-05-20/news/0805190369_1_civil-unions-same-sex-couples|title = With these words, let us wed|date = 2008-05-20|accessdate = |website = Chicago Tribune|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Puerto Rican Sodomy Law \u2013 An Irony of Gay History<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bilerico.com/2008/10/puerto_rican_sodomy_law_-_an_irony_of_ga.php#BWZWAYssLDg2g5gL.99|title = Puerto Rican Sodomy Law \u2013 An Irony of Gay History|date = 2008-10-15|accessdate = |website = The Bilerico Project|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* We are not equal \u2013 the abused second class Americans<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ambiente.us/12008CTMock.html|title = We are not equal \u2013 the abused second class Americans|date = December 2008|accessdate = |website = Ambiente|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Study Links Gay Marriage Bans to Rise in HIV Rate<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ambiente.us/06509CTMock.html|title = Study Links Gay Marriage Bans to Rise in HIV Rate|date = June 2009|accessdate = |website = Ambiente|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* In the embrace of her family<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-08-09/news/0908080205_1_mamita-final-goodbye-lace|title = In the embrace of her family|date = 2009-08-09|accessdate = |website = Chicago Tribune|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The American Solution for Puerto Rico<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ambiente.us/041511CTMock.html|title = The American Solution for Puerto Rico|date = April 2011|accessdate = |website = Ambiente|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n===Books===\n\n====Fiction====\n* Borrowing Time: A Latino Sexual Odyssey \u2013 Floricanto Press 2003. Paperback in 2006.\n* Mosaic Virus \u2013 Floricanto Press 2007.\n* Papi Chulo: A Legend, a Novel, and the Puerto Rican Identity \u2013 Floricanto Press 2008.\n*The Corner Queen\u2014La Loca de la Esquina: A Romance and a Revolution \u2014 Floricanto Press 2018.\n\n==== Non Fiction ====\n* Cuba Libe: \"Mentirita\" Cuba's history from the Afro Cuban point of view. - Floricanto Press October 2009.\n\n====Poetry====\n* Unfinished Works Published by AIDS Services Foundation \u2013 Orange County December 2005. \"The Critic\" Honorable Mention\n* The Refined Savage Poetry Review \u2013 Refined Savage Editions Issue 1, March 2006 Editor/Publisher Jose Alejandro Pe\u00f1a\n* Fingernails Across the Chalkboard Gwendolyn Brooks Center December 2006 Honorable Mention \"Winter\"\n* MARIPOSAS: A Modern Anthology of Queer Latino Poetry Edited by Emanuel Xavier. Published by Floricanto Press, October 12, 2008\n* Infinitas \u2013 Floricanto Press December 2011.\n\n====Short Stories====\n* Van Gogh's Ear \u2013 The Supernatural Edition Anthology edited by Felice Picano. Page 72: Santer\u00eda 101: How to Cconceive a Boy\n* Historias \u2013 Floricanto Press June 2014.  Nominated for The 2015 Pulitzer Prize<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.pulitzer.org|title = The Pulitzer Prizes|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>  in fiction;  Nominated for a 2015 International Latino Book Award<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lbff.us/bookawards14thnewyork.php|title = Latino Literacy Now|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141114123523/http://www.lbff.us/bookawards14thnewyork.php|archive-date = 2014-11-14|url-status = dead}}</ref>  in General Fiction, Nominated in 2015 for the Lammy award<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lambdaliterary.org|title = Lambda Literary|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> in Fiction from The Lambda Literary Foundation\n\n====Essays====\n* El Jard\u00edn de los Senderos que se Bifurcan by Jorge Lu\u00eds Borges B. A. in Latin American Literature Thesis,  Johns Hopkins University 1976.\n* Unfinished Works Published by AIDS Services Foundation \u2013 Orange County December 2005. \"HIV From the Puerto Rican Perspective\" - Third Place award\n* \"Queer History viewed through the eyes of Literature and my favorite books as I live my Latino Odyssey\" Testimonial Texts, Stories, Lives and Memories Published by Universidad Pedag\u00f3gica Nacional (UPN), Mexico City May, 2006\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.carlostmock.com/ Official Site]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Encyclopedia-Contemporary-Literature-United-volumes/dp/0313348596/ref=sr_1_9?ie=UTF8&qid=1410660061&sr=8-9&keywords=carlos+t+mock Encyclopedia of Contemporary LGBTQ Literature of the United States]\n* [http://www.floricantopress.com/ Floricanto Press]\n* [http://www.ambiente.us/ Ambiente Magazine]\n* [http://www.bilerico.com/ The Bilerico Project]\n* [http://www.opednews.com/ OpEd News]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mock, Carlos T.}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT novelists]]\n[[Category:People from San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:People from Three Oaks, Michigan]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language LGBT writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name             = Carlos T. Mock\n| image            = CarlosTMock.jpg\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1956|01|16|mf=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]\n| language         = [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[French language|French]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Johns Hopkins University]], [[University of Puerto Rico School of Medicine]]\n| occupation       = [[Physician]] [[Ob/Gyn]], [[activist]], [[novelist]], [[poet]]\n| nationality      = American ([[Puerto Rican people|Puerto Rican]])\n| partner          = Bill Rattan\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.carlostmock.com/|www.CarlosTMock.com}}\n}}\n\nDr. '''Carlos T. Mock''' (born January 16, 1956) is a Puerto Rican physician, gay activist, journalist, and writer who has published both works in the medical profession, works of fiction, non-fiction, and poetry.\n\n==Life==\nMock was born in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]].  He left Puerto Rico upon graduating from high school and attended [[The Johns Hopkins University]] in Baltimore, Maryland where he graduated [[Cum Laude]] in 1976 with a BA with a double major in Chemistry and Spanish Literature.  He then attended The [[University of Puerto Rico School of Medicine]] in San Juan where he obtained a [[Physician|MD]] in 1980.\n\nHe then did a flexible [[Internship (medicine)|internship]] at the [[United States Public Health Service|USPH]] Service Hospital in [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] and then did a four-year residency in [[Obstetrics and gynaecology|Obstetrics and Gynecology]] at [[Stroger Hospital|Cook County Hospital]] in [[Chicago, Illinois]], graduating in 1985.\n\nMock then joined a private place group at the Glen Ellyn Clinic where he practiced Obstetrics and Gynecology until 1996.  He developed an interest in [[infertility]] and [[twin]] pregnancies which led to the publication of a medical paper in the later topic.\n\nHe is a Life Fellow of the [[American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists]] and a Life Member of the [[American Medical Association]].\n\nDue to complications from [[HIV]] therapy, he became disabled in May 1996.  He currently lives in Chicago, Illinois and [[Three Oaks, Michigan]] with his partner, Bill Rattan.\n\n==Activism==\nWhile at practice in the Glen Ellyn Clinic, Mock experienced first-hand the discrimination in the workforce against [[GLBT]] physicians when one of his colleagues was fired for being gay.  This, along with his HIV diagnosis, which forced him to retire, caused him to join the Board of [[Equality Illinois]] where he founded the Capitol Club.,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.chicagogayhistory.com/biography.html?id=771|title = Chicago Gay History|date = 2007-05-23|accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> the fundraising arm of the organization, where he served from 2000 until 2009.  His fundraising efforts were instrumental in the passage of the Human Rights Act of Illinois in 2005,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www3.illinois.gov/pressreleases/ShowPressRelease.cfm?SubjectID=3&RecNum=3636 |title=Illinois Government News Network |date=January 21, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143112/http://www3.illinois.gov/pressreleases/ShowPressRelease.cfm?SubjectID=3&RecNum=3636 |archivedate=2015-04-27 }}</ref> prohibiting discrimination based upon sexual orientation and gender identity in Illinois. For his work he was inducted into the [[Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame]] in 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chicagolgbthalloffame.org/mock-carlos/|title=Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n\n==Literary career==\nMock started writing in 2001.  He was first published in 2003 when Floricanto Press published Borrowing Time, A Latino Sexual Odyssey, which was later released in paperback in 2006.  This was followed by five other publications.  Since then he has contributed to The [[Chicago Tribune]], [[Windy City Times]], Ambiente Magazine (in Miami, Florida) and the web magazines: The Billerico Project and OpEd News.\n\n==Publications==\n\n===Articles===\n* Twin Reversed Arterial Perfusion Syndrome, acephalic presentating at full term, Robert Roger Lebel, MD, Carlos Mock, MD, Jeannette Israel, MD, William Senica, MD, Fetus Magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.sonoworld.com/fetus/page.aspx?id=309|title = Twin reversed arterial perfusion syndrome, acephalic presenting at full term|date = 2 June 1994|accessdate = |website = Fetus Magazine|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Mock Views:  The Death of a Great Pope<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Mock-Views-The-Death-of-a-Great-Pope/7948.html|title = Mock Views: The Death of a Great Pope|date = 2005-04-13|accessdate = |website = Windy City Times|publisher = Windy City Media Group|last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The New Faces of Puerto Rican Lesbian Activism<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/The-New-