1ebeb\" | [[Proto-Turkic language|Proto-Turkic]]\n|  rowspan=\"17\" bgcolor=\"#d6e1ec\" | [[Common Turkic languages|Common Turkic]]\n|  rowspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" style=\"border-left:none;\"| [[Oghuz languages|Southwestern Common Turkic (Oghuz)]]\n[[File:Oghuzlanguages6.png|upright=0.45|frameless]]\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" style=\"border-right:none;\"| &nbsp;\n|\n* [[Pecheneg language|Pecheneg]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | West Oghuz\n|\n* [[Old Anatolian Turkish]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Turkish language|Turkish]]\n* [[Iraqi Turkmens#Language|Iraqi Turkmen]]\n* [[Gagauz language|Gagauz]]\n* [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]\n* [[Balkan Gagauz Turkish language|Balkan Gagauz Turkish]]\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | East Oghuz\n|\n* [[Turkmen language|Turkmen]]\n* [[Khorasani Turkic language|Khorasani Turkic]]\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | South Oghuz\n|\n* [[Afshar language|Afshar]]\n* Dialects of Iran such as [[Qashqai language|Qashqai]], [[Sonqori language|Sonqori]], [[Aynallu language|Aynallu]], etc.\n|-\n|  bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" | (Arghu)\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" | &nbsp;\n|\n* [[Khalaj language|Khalaj]]<ref>Khalaj is surrounded by Oghuz languages, but exhibits a number of features that classify it as non-Oghuz.</ref>\n|-\n|  rowspan=\"4\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" style=\"border-left:none;\"| [[Kypchak languages|Northwestern Common Turkic (Kipchak)]]\n[[File:Map-Kypchak Language World.png|upright=0.45|frameless]]\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" style=\"border-right:none;\"| &nbsp;\n|\n* [[Kipchak language|Kipchak]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | West Kipchak\n|\n* [[Kumyk language|Kumyk]]\n* [[Karachay-Balkar language|Karachay-Balkar]]\n* [[Crimean Tatar language|Crimean Tatar]], [[Urum language|Urum]]<ref>Crimean Tatar and Urum are historically Kipchak languages, but have been heavily influenced by Oghuz languages.</ref>\n* [[Krymchak language|Krymchak]]\n* [[Cuman language|Cuman]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Karaim language|Karaim]]\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | North Kipchak (Volga\u2013Ural Turkic)\n|\n* [[Tatar language|Tatar]]\n* [[Bashkir language|Bashkir]]\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | South Kipchak (Aralo-Caspian)\n|\n* [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]]\n* [[Karakalpak language|Karakalpak]]\n* [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]]<ref name=\"turcologica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.turkiclanguages.com/www/classification.html|title=turcologica|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Fergana Kipchak language|Kipchak Uzbek (Fergana Kipchak language)]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Siberian Tatar language|Siberian Tatar]]<ref>Tura, Baraba, Tomsk, T\u00fcmen, Ishim, Irtysh, Tobol, Tara, etc. are partly of different origin (Johanson 1998) [http://www.turkiclanguages.com/www/classification.html]</ref>\n* [[Nogai language|Nogay]]\n|-\n|  rowspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" | [[Karluk languages|Southeastern Common Turkic (Karluk)]]\n[[File:Lenguas karluk.png|upright=0.45|frameless]]\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | West\n|\n* [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]]\n|-\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | East\n|\n* [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]]\n* Taranchi\n* [[Salar language|Salar]]<ref>Deviating. Historically developed from Southwestern (Oghuz) (Johanson 1998) [http://www.turkiclanguages.com/www/classification.html]</ref>\n* [[Chagatai language|Chagatai]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Aini language|Aini]]<ref>Aini contains a very large [[Persian language|Persian]] vocabulary component, and is spoken exclusively by adult men, almost as a [[cryptolect]].</ref>\n* [[Ili Turki language|Ili Turki]]\n|-\n|  rowspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"#e4e0f0\" | [[Siberian Turkic languages|Northeastern Common Turkic (Siberian)]]\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | North Siberian\n|\n* [[Sakha language|Sakha]] (Yakut)\n* [[Dolgan language|Dolgan]]\n|-\n|  rowspan=\"5\" bgcolor=\"#f1e9df\" | South Siberian\n|  bgcolor=\"#f1dfe5\" | Sayan Turkic\n|\n* [[Tuvan language|Tuvan]] (Soyot, Uriankhai)\n* [[Tofa language|Tofa]]\n|-\n|  bgcolor=\"#f1dfe5\" | Yenisei Turkic\n|\n* [[Khakas language|Khakas]]\n* [[Fuy\u00fc G\u00efrg\u00efs language|Fuy\u00fc G\u00efrg\u00efs]]\n* [[Shor language|Shor]] (Saghay Qaca, Qizil)\n* [[Western Yugur language|Western Yugur]] (Yellow Uyghur)<ref name=\"turcologica\" /><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7XuMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA7 Coene 2009], p. 75</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=FqFMmVbfRfEC&pg=PA75 Coene 2009], p. 75</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Concise Encyclopedia of Languages of the World|first=|last=|volume=|others=Contributors Keith Brown, Sarah Ogilvie|edition=revised|year=2010|publisher=Elsevier|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F2SRqDzB50wC&pg=PA1109 |page=1109|isbn=978-0080877754|accessdate=24 April 2014| ref=harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Mainz Meeting: Proceedings of the Seventh International Conference on Turkish Linguistics, August 3\u20136, 1994|series=Turcologica Series|editor-first=Lars|editor-last=Johanson|volume=|others=Contributor \u00c9va \u00c1gnes Csat\u00f3|edition=|year=1998|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cgNQdljvk70C&pg=PA28 |page=28|isbn=978-3447038645|accessdate=24 April 2014| ref=harv }}</ref>\n|-\n|  bgcolor=\"f1dfe5\" | Chulym Turkic\n|\n* [[Chulym language|Chulym]] (K\u00fcerik)\n|-\n|  bgcolor=\"f1dfe5\" | Altai Turkic<ref name=\"turcologica\" />\n|\n* [[Altay language|Altay]] Oirot and dialects such as Tuba, Qumanda, Qu, Teleut, Telengit\n|-\n|  bgcolor=\"f1dfe5\" | Old Turkic\n|\n* [[Orkhon Turkic language|Orkhon Turkic]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Old Uyghur language|Old Uyghur]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n|-\n|  bgcolor=\"#d6e1ec\" | [[Oghur languages|Oghur]]\n|  bgcolor=\"#d6e1ec\" | &nbsp;\n|  colspan=\"2\" bgcolor=\"#d6e1ec\" | &nbsp;\n|\n* [[Chuvash language|Chuvash]] \n* [[Khazar language|Khazar]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n* [[Bulgar language|Bulgar]] <small>(extinct)</small>\n|}\n</div>\n\n==Vocabulary comparison==\n{{Expert-subject|2=section|date=November 2010}}\nThe following is a brief comparison of [[cognate]]s among the basic vocabulary across the Turkic language family (about 60 words).\n\nEmpty cells do not necessarily imply that a particular language is lacking a word to describe the concept, but rather that the word for the concept in that language may be formed from another stem and is not a cognate with the other words in the row or that a [[loanword]] is used in its place.\n\nAlso, there may be shifts in the meaning from one language to another, and so the \"Common meaning\" given is only approximate. In some cases the form given is found only in some dialects of the language, or a loanword is much more common (e.g. in Turkish, the preferred word for \"fire\" is the Persian-derived ''ate\u015f'', whereas the native ''od'' is dead). Forms are given in native Latin orthographies unless otherwise noted.\n<!--\nThis is a cognate table, so please do not add any non-cognates -->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n!\n!Common meaning\n!style=\"background-color: #d6e1ec\"|'''[[Proto-Turkic language|Proto-Turkic]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #d1ebeb\"|'''[[Old Turkic language|Old Turkic]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #d6e1ec\"|'''[[Turkish language|Turkish]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #e4e0f0\"|'''[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]]'''\n![[Qashqai language|Qashqai]]\n!style=\"background-color: #ece0f0\"|'''[[Turkmen language|Turkmen]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #f1dfe5\"|'''[[Tatar language|Tatar]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #f1e9df\"|'''[[Bashkir language|Bashkir]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #f1e9df\"|'''[[Kazakh language|Kazakh]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #d6e1ec\"|'''[[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]]'''\n!style=\"background-color: #f0f1df\"|'''[[Uzbek language|Uzbek]]'''\n